<h1>Wine Tools</h1>

       
       Here are a number of tools which may be useful for Wine developers and
       Wine users.
       Some are Windows platform, and some are Unix.
       
      
<p><hr size=2 noshade><p>

       <h2> Browsing the Wine source </h2>
       Thanks to <a href="http://lxr.linux.no/">LXR</a>, WineHQ provides
       <ul>
         <li> <a href="/source">http://www.winehq.com/source</a> Cross-referenced,
         marked up source
         <li> <a href="/ident">http://www.winehq.com/ident</a> Identifier location 
         (where it's defined, everywhere it's used) 
         <li> <a href="/search">http://www.winehq.com/search</a> Full-text search.
       </ul>
       Similar but less complete 
       functionality is available locally by using tags in emacs or vi.
       
       <h2> Windows development tools </h2>
       <h3> Win32 SDKs </h3>
       <ul> 
         <li> <A HREF="http://sources.redhat.com/cygwin/">Cygwin</a> Cygnus's 
           port of GCC and GNU toolchain for Win32 (now owned by Red Hat). Includes
           complete environment for porting Unix software to Win32 platforms.
           <a href="ftp://ftp.deninc.com/">Mirror</a> Including Sergey Ohkapin's work.
         <li> <a href="http://www.mingw.org/">MinGW</a> &quot;Minimalist&quot; GNU toolchain, based on Cygwin32, 
       aimed at those not needing the Unix system calls
       provided by Cygwin32's cygwin.dll
         <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.coda.cs.cmu.edu/pub/tools/">Cygwin32 for Linux</a> Binary and source RPMs of Cygwin32 compiled for Linux by Peter Braam.
         <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.mathematik.uni-bielefeld.de/pub/tex/systems/msdos/dpmigcc/">RSXNT</a> 
	 Another GCC port.
         <li> <a href="http://www.cs.virginia.edu/~lcc-win32/">LCC-Win32</a>
       LCC is a free win32 compiler/development environment. 
       Includes win32 compiler, assembler, linker, header files, resource compiler,
       Wedit editor, and various other tools. Smaller, simpler, and less sophisticated
       than GNU toolchain. Entertaining documentation.
        Also see the
       <a href="http://www.geocities.com/SiliconValley/Heights/9069/">Unofficial homepage</a>.
       Works under Wine.
         <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.mathematik.tu-darmstadt.de:/pub/linux/bonnes/lcc-linux-announce">LCC-Linux</a> LCC tools (compiler, linker, resource compiler, PE dumper, make, and lburg) ported to Linux. <a href="ftp://ftp.mathematik.tu-darmstadt.de:/pub/linux/bonnes/lcc-unixbin-alpha.tar.gz">Unix binaries</a>
         <li> <a href="http://www.planet.net/pjoshv/cross-elf.html">Cross-ELF</a> Produce win32 code under Linux, support DOS, Linux, and win32 with a single executable
         <li> <a href="http://www.winsite.com/free/freeutil/">WinSite utils</a> Win95 tools courtesy UI archive
       </ul>
       
       <h3> Win16 SDKs </h3>
       There are lots of commercial environments. I'd appreciate links to other
       free ones.
       <ul>
         <li> <a href="http://www.delorie.com/djgpp/">DJGPP</a> A DOS compiler based
              on GCC. It will run under Linux using <a>DOSEMU</a>. 
	      There is <a href="http://www.delorie.com/djgpp/16bit/">partial
	      support</a> for producing and linking 16-bit code.
             <a href="http://www.delorie.com/djgpp/v2faq/faq3_6.html">
             with trouble and additional tools</a>.
         <li> <a href="ftp://x2ftp.oulu.fi/pub/msdos/programming/djgpp2/">DJGPP2</a>
         <li> <a href="ftp://x2ftp.oulu.fi/pub/msdos/programming/djgpp2/xlib031.txt">xlib-emu</a> Wrappers for Xlib calls allow porting X programs to pure DOS systems
       </ul>
       
       <h3> Resource Compilers </h3>
       Yes, I know that these are usually part of SDKs, so most of the
       environments listed above will come with resource compilers.
       <ul>
         <li> <a href="/source/tools/wrc/README.wrc">wrc</a> The Wine resource compiler
	 <li> <a>Twin rc</a>
	 <li> <a>windres</a> Part of binutils 2.9.1.
       </ul>

       <h2> Utilities </h2>
       <ul> 
         <li> <a href="http://www.cs.colorado.edu/homes/zorn/public_html/MallocDebug.html">MallocDebug</a> Nice set of links on malloc debugging tools
         <li> <a href="http://www.cse.ogi.edu/DISC/projects/immunix/StackGuard/">StackGuard</a> GCC extension to detect stack smashing
         <li> <a href="ftp://dse.doc.ic.ac.uk/pub/misc/bcc">Bcc</a> Bounds checking  patch for GCC.
         <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.winehq.com/pub/wine/disasm.tar.gz">PE disassembler</a> By Sang Cho, ported by Uwe Bonnes. Also available <a href="ftp://elektron.ikp.physik.tu-darmstadt.de/pub/disasm.tar.gz">here</a>, or see the original
       <a href="http://www.simtel.net/pub/simtelnet/win95/prog/disassem.zip">here</a>.
         <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.sunsite.org.uk/Mirrors/ftp.cdrom.com/pub/simtelnet/msdos/disasm/ida37fw.zip">IDA</a> Interactive Disassembler
         <li> <a href="http://www.alphalink.com.au/~mvertes/xlab.html">XLab</a> (broken link)
