       Wine has the following useful utilities builtin:
       <ul> 
         <li> debugger 
       	<br> Understands both segmented and flat addresses, Unix and Windows
                    symbol tables, and lots of other stuff.
               <br> Invoke by either a) Using <code>winedbg</code> instead of <code>wine</code> on the command line.
                    b) waiting for Wine or the Windows program to crash.
         <li> system call tracer / API spy (-debugmsg +relay), 
         <li> message tracer (-debugmsg +message)
         <li> disassembler (disass while inside debugger)
       </ul>
       
       <h3> Other utilities </h3>
       <ul> 
       <li><a>pedump</a> File dumper for 32-bit PE executables.
       A good one (based on code distributed with
       <a href="index.php?refs#w95secrets">Windows 95 System Programming Secrets</a>) is available as part of the 
       <a href="http://www.cs.virginia.edu/~lcc-win32/index.html">LCC</a>
        environment. The ELF equivalent is <code>objdump</code>.
       <li> <a>file (1)</a> This standard Unix utility can 
       recognize various kinds of DOS/Windows executables and give a small amount of information about them.
       <li> <a>whead</a> Header dumper for 16-bit NE executables. Included with Twin.
       <li> <a href="http://www.anatom.uni-tuebingen.de/~richi/linux/binfmt_misc.html">binfmt_misc</a> Linux kernel patch to recognize
       DOS/Windows/Java executables as the natively supported formats they are. Available as a patch to Linux 2.0.x, and it is integrated into 2.1.43 
       and above.
         <li> API Spy for Windows. There are several, including free ones.
       </ul>
       
       
       <h2> X displays for Windows </h2>
       Remote display of Windows apps (running under Wine on a Unix server) to 
       Unix client desktops is as easy as any
       other X program. (For tips on remote X display,
       see the <a href="http://www.linuxdoc.org/HOWTO/mini/Remote-X-Apps.html">Remote X mini-HOWTO</a> for many details.)
       It's nearly as easy to deliver to a Windows desktop,  but
       you need an X display running on the Windows desktop. Here are a few, for
       a more exhaustive list, with reviews, see 
       <a href="http://www.rahul.net/kenton/xsites.html#XMicrosoft">Ken Lee</a>'s site.
       <ul>
         <li> <a href="http://xfree86.cygwin.com/">Cygwin/XFree86</a> - Windows port of XFree86.
         <li> <a href="http://tnt.microimages.com/www/html/freestuf/mix/">Mix</a>
       Free X server for Windows (it seems however latest versions became commercial)
         <li> <a href="http://www.starnet.com/">x-win32</a> Shareware X-Server for Windows
         <li> <a href="http://www.hummingbird.com/products/nc/exceed/">Exceed</a> Commercial X-Server for Windows from <a href="http://www.hummingbird.com/">Hummingbird</a>
         <li> <a href="http://www.wrq.com/products/evaluate/download/rxchoice.html">Reflection X</a> Free time-locked demo.
         <li> <a href="http://www.xtreme.it/xappeal/">XAppeal</a> DOS. Based on X11R6 
         and XFree. Shareware / commercial.
       
       </ul>
       
       
       <h2> Fonts </h2>
       <h3> Browsing, viewing, installing </h3>
       Most of these come with any version of X. Consult their man pages
       for details.
       <ul>
         <li> xlsfonts, fslsfonts -- list available fonts from X server or a
	      font server
	 <li> fsinfo -- information about a font server
	 <li> mkfontdir -- create the fonts.dir file for a directory (part of
	 installing a font)
	 <li> <a href="http://www.darmstadt.gmd.de/~pommnitz/ttmkfdir.tar.gz">ttmkfdir</a> Like mkfontdir, but for TTF fonts. Not a part of X.
	 <li> <a href="http://rpmfind.net/linux/RPM/type1inst.html">type1inst</a> Like mkfontdir, but for Type 1 fonts. (Also see <a href="http://aix2.uottawa.ca/~s1204672/linux/gglyph/patch-type1inst.diff">this patch</a>).
	 <li> xset q, xset fp -- query / alter the font path used by the X server
	 <li> xfontsel, xfd -- select / view a font
	 <li> showfont -- dump a font from a font server. (Not to be confused 
	 with the Linux console showfont -- this one is installed as /usr/X11R6/bin/showfont.)
	 <li> <a href="http://filewatcher.org/sec/gglyph.html">GGlyph</a> T1 previewer, installer. GTK based.
       </ul>
       <h3> Conversion </h3>
       <ul>
         <li> fnt2bdf -- included with Wine
	 <li> fstobdf -- output any font known to a font server in BDF format. Standard X utility.
	 <li> <a href="ftp://prep.ai.mit.edu/pub/gnu/fontutils/fontutils-0.7.tar.gz">
	 fontutils</a> GNU tools from FSF (also see
	 <a href="http://www-personal.engin.umich.edu/~jgotts/projects/fontutils.diff">
	 Linux patch</a>) Bitmap to outline conversion, bitmap editing.
	 Works with TeX and PostScript formats.
         <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.univie.ac.at/packages/tex/fonts/utilities/ttf2pt1/">ttf2pfa</a> TrueType to Postscript Type 3
	 <li> <a href="http://www.netspace.net.au/~mheath/ttf2pt1/">ttf2pt1</a> TrueType to Postscript Type 1
	 <li> <a>ttf2bdf</a> --  Use a TTF font server and fstobdf, or ttf2bdf in FreeType contrib
	 <li> <a>ttf2pfb</a> -- See FreeType contrib
	 <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.freetype.org/pub/freetype/">ttfdump</a> Display information about a TTF font
	 <li> <a href="ftp://ftp.blueneptune.com/pub/users/ram/misc/t1utils.tar.gz">t1utils</a> PostScript Type 1 to/from human readable ASCII converters
       </ul>
       <h3> Font Servers </h3>
       Font servers allow the task of rendering fonts to be delegated to 
       another process, possibly on another machine. Add a font server to
       your font path with a command like <code>xset fp+ tcp/machinename:7100</code>.
       <ul>
         <li> xfs -- the standard X font server, which can deal with standard X fonts. This is the building block for most other font servers.
	 <li> <a 
	 href="http://www.dcs.ed.ac.uk/home/jec/programs/xfsft/">xfsft</a> --
	 xfs extended to deal with TTF fonts using <a href="http://www.freetype.org/">FreeType</a>.
	 <li> <a href="http://hawk.ise.chuo-u.ac.jp/student/person/tshiozak/x-tt/index-eng.html">X-TT</a> Another extension to xfs using Freetype. This one
	 implements lazy glyph rendering, which is crucial for East Asian
	 fonts.
  <li> <a href="http://www.netlab.is.tsukuba.ac.jp/~yokota/izumi/Xatm/">Xatm</a> xfs extended for Postscript fonts, using Ghostscript. Web page is Japanese.
	 <li> <a href="ftp://sunsite.unc.edu/pub/Linux/X11/fonts/">Xfstt</a>
	 A TTF-only font server. Simple to configure.
	 <li> Commercial: the font servers shipped with Solaris 2.6, Irix 6.3,
	AIX 4.3.3
	 and the Fontastic server that comes with Applixware can all serve TTF
	 fonts.
       </ul>
